              <div class="quotetitle">Gulielmus wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Meh. Parsing based on the distinction between technology and magic, the narrative type, mechanics, whatever, is just silly. What it basically amounts to is whether a book &quot;feels&quot; like science fiction or &quot;feels&quot; like fantasy — or whether the author or publisher doesn't want it to be classified as either. Genres are stupid for this exact reason. <br /></div><br /><br />Oh, absolutely.<br /><br />The line is fuzzy, but the distinction is still useful and some things are very clearly on one side or the other.  The distinction becomes less useful as we move away from physical bookstores which need to divide by genres for browsers.<br /><br />For the original question, I'd say science fiction even though a certain amount of mysticism is involved.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
