              <div class="quotetitle">Gulielmus wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Meh. Parsing based on the distinction between technology and magic, the narrative type, mechanics, whatever, is just silly. What it basically amounts to is whether a book &quot;feels&quot; like science fiction or &quot;feels&quot; like fantasy — or whether the author or publisher doesn't want it to be classified as either. Genres are stupid for this exact reason. <br /><br />Margaret Atwood writes some fantastic science-fiction-like stories, but she insists she doesn't write science fiction (and was quoted as specifying martians, teleporters, and intergalactic space travel as particular qualities of sci-fi). Instead, she says she writes &quot;speculative fiction.&quot; It gets her on the &quot;literary fiction&quot; bookshelves in the stores anyway. But there's no reason someone who browses the sci-fi section shouldn't give her the same chance as someone who browses the literary fiction section. This is just one example.<br /><br />Genres suck.</div><br /><br /> What Sci-Fi section in the book store?  Any store I've been in lately has mixed the Sci-Fi and Fantasy together and I hate it.  Hell even Amazon.com has mixed stuff up.  As much as I hate labels I want to read about technology and interesting speculation on how it will evolve and the sociological implications it would bring.  Not a story about a big quest for some magical bauble.  <br /><br /> In that respect Genres are great.<br /><br /><br /> Since we are kinda on the subject of Dune (or were) I couple years ago I read somewhere, someone comparing Dune (in movie form) to another movie that was drastically different but when you looked deeper was actually pretty similar.  Does anyone have any clue what that movie may be? I'm not even sure it was Sci-fi.

              

              
              
            </div>
