              <div class="quotetitle">NotContinuum wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The Foundation Series is interesting, but when you read it now, you realize how incredibly out-of-date it is.  Still, it's pretty good, considering it was written a long time ago.<br /><br />As for Dune... I'd say it's more fantasy.  More appropriately, it's science fantasy. (As opposed to science fiction)  It uses the future and future technology/science to set up an epic and the rules behind the universe.  The prohibition on using computers for space flight (along with it's life-prolonging effects) sets up the need for Melange and its importance.  It's a plot device necessary to make the motivations for control of Arakis realistic.  But in the end, it just sets up the universe.  Science isn't really used to carry the story forward or solve the main problems.<br /><br />Star Trek is most definitely science fiction because of how it uses science not only to set up the universe but as a way of carrying the story forward and even solving the main problem.</div><br /><br />Yeah, Melange couldn't possibly be a substitute for some other substance we'd need to sustain our economy and society, like Oil, or Power.  Totally not.<br /><br />It's science fiction, but really it's just allegory.  It's practically the middle-east and the constant warring and fighting to control oil by outside powers retold with different names.  All of the rest is window dressing.<br /><br />Calling it fantasy seems a bit off to me, given it's direct correlation to our recent past and current time frames.  There are obviously several things which are not substitutes for something already existing (i.e. facedancers) but frankly, that's the science fiction part.  I'd argue that most of the technology, philosophy, etc is plausible.<br /><br />I don't really think you start getting into anything remotely LIKE fantasy until you have the Quizatsadurak (not sure how the fuck you spell that), and even that is just a plausible extension of the powers of the Bene Jesuit.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
