        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Dune is a mix of sci-fi and fantasy. There's a decent amount of &quot;magic&quot; there, but it's the kind that was common in sci-fi of the 60s-80s, driven by the idea that just maybe LSD trips were more than the mental equivalent of pushing on an LCD screen to see the pretty pictures. I consider it real sci-fi because most of the non mental stuff was based in science. All the tech for living in an extreme desert environment, the life-cycle of the sandworms, the reasoning for not using computers, etc, it's all sci-fi, pretty hard sci-fi for the time. Terraforming and environmentalism weren't pervasive like they are now, 99.5% of people didn't think that the environment was changeable. Even things like the mentats were grounded in science, without the ability to use computers there almost certainly would be a lot of effort put into utilizing savants.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The Foundation Series is interesting, but when you read it now, you realize how incredibly out-of-date it is. Still, it's pretty good, considering it was written a long time ago.</div><br />Asimov was one of the best futurists and idea men sci-fi has had, but he wasn't a particularly great writer. He was better than most of his contemporaries, but there's a reason sci-fi was a second class literary citizen for a long time. All I can think of when reading him or Clarke now is how dated it feels. A part of that is that they are a victim of their own success, we're pretty much living in some of the sci-fi they imagined, which makes it seem mundane with details that are &quot;off&quot;. &quot;Why is he giving some awkward description of what a satellite is?&quot; Checks publication date. &quot;Oh, satellites didn't exist then...&quot;<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Science fiction or fantasy? Really? <br /><br />Who the fuck cares?</div><br />The Internet!<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">And genres are the bane of literature. Would you enjoy Dune any more or less if it were &quot;high fantasy&quot;, &quot;science fiction&quot;, &quot;future fantasy&quot; or whatever? Would it be any less or more or a classic? Would you think any differently about the themes? I certainly don't think so.</div><br />The discussion here is a thought exercise, because, &quot;why not?&quot; Genres serve an extremely important purpose in the general sense though, because they steer people towards the kind of books they enjoy. Sometimes there are books that don't fit in any of the slots, and that's ok (most books hit multiple genres these days), but generally when you go pick up a &quot;sci-fi&quot; book with spaceships on the cover you have an idea of what you are going to get. Aside from the fact that the lines can blur, fantasy/sci-fi is considered one section in the bookstore because the demographics for both are more or less the same, and genres are about getting books in front of the people who have the most chance of liking them.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Funny. I think &quot;God Emperor of Dune&quot; is easily the best book in the series. It's the only one I occasionally will re-read.</div><br />The thing with the dune books is that they were all pretty great (the second and third are definitely the weakest), but they were very different kinds of books. If you went into GEoD expecting Dune, you were going to be sorely disappointed. It's the same thing with Ender's Game to Speaker for the Dead, SftD is fantastic 80s sci-fi, but it's nothing like EG.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">It's science fiction, but really it's just allegory. It's practically the middle-east and the constant warring and fighting to control oil by outside powers retold with different names. All of the rest is window dressing.</div><br />I would argue that the allegorical fight over the spice is the widow dressing, and the other elements are the meat of it.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
