        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              More generally, I classify something as sci-fi if the science is plausible or believable, and if it's the motivator for the story. A true sci-fi story can't be told without major modifications if you stripped out the science. It's about exploring the human condition when confronted with future-tech and the dilemmas it brings. If there's no real science there then it might as well be magic (SW) and it's fantasy. Boiled down, fantasy is just sci-fi without any attempt to ground it in reality. <br /><br />Sci-fi itself is a thing because grounding in reality generally ends up making things a lot more interesting and unexpected than if you just make shit up. For example, trying to fit real quantum physics into sci-fi books has produced a lot of crazy and interesting story elements that would be dismissed as unbelievable nonsense if they didn't have the science backing. The same thing with relativity, there is so much sci-fi that gets mileage out of relativity, whereas no fantasy author is going to come up with something that complicated and bizarre.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
