        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle">Dac wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The 'argument' or point of view over what constitutes Science Fiction, and what comprises Fantasy, has been mulled over many times over the decades.  <br /><br />The bookshelves in shops (back when bookshops were the only way to get books) were filled with fantasy, and interspersed within were 'Proper' SF authors.  Heroic/Fantasy fiction abounds, and seems to be devoured by the paying customers, whilst SF is still 'nerdy/geeky' and never quite as popular to be able to give it the same shelf-space as the burgeoning Fantasy section.<br /><br />As with diverse musical 'forms' (rap, hiphop, dance, ska, rock, jazz, etc), there are shades of SF which any aficionado could rattle off, but most 'mundane' people would shrug off as 'it's all the same to me, mate'.  <br /><br />There will be people who cite Clarke/Asimov/Heinlein as 'SF' and Tolkien as 'Fantasy'.  There's work out there like (the hateful) Ray Bradbury or the distinctly odd John Wyndham, classified as SF, but it's hardly science, and mostly suggestion, wordsmithery, literature.  All shady unknowns and mayhap, rather than descriptions of glowing dials, hardware, and coruscating ravening beams of hyperdyned destruction.<br /><br />I like my SF to be 'diamond hard', Neal Stephenson, Iain M. Banks etc.  A lot of readers prefer softer SF authors, Anne McCaffrey, for example.<br /><br />There's nothing to be gained by pigeonholing authors, or specific books, into what -you- believe is their correct nomenclature. There is nothing to be had by forcing a group of people to agree that X is SF and Y is Fantasy.  It's all very arbitrary labeling, and in many cases, simply misguided.<br /><br />Classify Pratchett's Discworld as Fantasy? More like comic genius.<br /><br />What about Piers Anthony's and his Xanth books; overwrought puns and puerile teenage masturbatory rubbish, if it was labeled 'correctly' <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/smile.png" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />Whatever the wider readership thinks what 'category' books should be in, at the end of the day, it's only a label.  The books themselves are what matters, and a good story trumps categorization.<br /><br />Dune is a damn fine story.</div><br /><br />I prefer to think of fiction as historical, speculative, satirical or fantastical.  The setting really has little to do with this, and is a second adjective you can throw in to add flavor.  So Game of Thrones is a combination of medieval fantasy, as it has mostly &quot;real&quot; political games with a bit of fantasy magic thrown in to color the world.  Neal Stephenson writes satirical speculative future fiction, as most of his work is based on playing out technology and politics to make points about human nature.  Dune is a hybrid of medieval futuristic satire, using spice in place of modern resources to comment on politics and religion.  Something like Old Man's War is fantastical futuristic satire.  Dragonlance or Battletech or Star Wars are just fantastical, with the appropriate setting adjective thrown in. <br /><br />The old &quot;fantasy&quot; and &quot;scifi&quot; monikers fail to encompass what the other is trying to achieve.  Are they trying for just a good story, or are they trying to make thematic points?  Both are okay, but reducing to simply setting fails at giving me any idea as to what the book is.<br /><br />In my opinion, the best fiction uses science or fantasy to explore topics relevant to our current lives.  By choosing a fictional settings and constructing science or magic, a good writer can focus the themes of his work on the specific issues he or she wants to address.  World-building in the name of the message.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
