              <div class="quotetitle">Agathos wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Fantasy? Only if ecology isn't a hard enough science to count. For my money, Dune ranks just behind the Mars trilogy if you're looking for a science fiction novel about terraforming.</div><br /><br />I'm currently reading <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_trilogy" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">this</a> right now (halfway through book 2). I'm usually into future military/space opera scifi (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_Fleet" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Lost Fleet</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karen_Traviss#Gears_of_War_series" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Gears of War</a>, <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Helforts-War-Book-Battle-ebook/dp/B000W7KNK8" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Helfort's war</a> etc.) for pleasure reading. There's some good classics in that vein too (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Starship_troopers" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Starship troopers</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armor_%28novel%29" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Armor</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battlefield_Earth_%28novel%29" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Battlefield Earth</a>) I occasionally drift into hard scifi (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold_series" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Manifold</a>). I do appreciate the Mars trilogy for its discussion of the sociopolitical ramifications and scientific speculations of terraforming Mars, but <span style="font-style: italic">goddamn</span> is it boring. I don't like leaving a series unfinished, but this one is becoming tedious for me.  <img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/sad.png" alt=":(" title="Frown" /><br /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Paul M wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">No bookstores I know of separate out Science Fiction and Fantasy.  They're all in the same section for a reason.</div><br /><br />This right here pisses me off. One reason I hate going to Brick and Mortar shops is due to this mindset. I don't want to wade through a huge selection of books about scantily clad people riding dragons and swinging swords to find my future military scifi. There can be <span style="font-style: italic">some</span> division. I can't remember where it was (been a while since I was in the market for dead-tree books), but I do remember being in a large book chain that had a subdivided scifi section. It was there that my faith in humanity was slightly restored. Fortunately, preferred recommendations (like on Amazon.com), combined with going completely digital, have made this argument moot for me.<br /><br /><br /><br /><img src="http://25.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lyuui7AVb11r95m39o1_500.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />Also:<br /><br /><img src="http://www.demotivationalposters.org/image/demotivational-poster/0908/books-demotivational-poster-1249878054.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><br /><br />-mhac³

              

              
              
